The '''National Museum of Civil War Medicine''' is a U.S. historic education institution located in [[Frederick, Maryland]]. Its focus involves the medical, surgical and nursing practices during the [[American Civil War]] (1861-1865).

== History ==
The museum, which was originally proposed by Dr. Gordon E. Damman, a private collector of Civil War-era medical artifacts, was incorporated in 1990 and first opened to the public in 1996.<ref>{{cite news | author = | title =Museum History | publisher =National Museum of Civil War Medicine | date = | url =http://civilwarmed.org/information/MuseumHistory.aspx | accessdate=2009-03-11}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> The museum moved into its current location – a three-story 19th century brick building that was home to a furniture maker/undertaker operation during the Civil War – in October 2000.<ref>{{cite news | author = | title =National Museum of Civil War Medicine Reopens Oct. 21 in Maryland | publisher =Civil War News | date =October 2000 | url =http://www.civilwarnews.com/archive/articles/natmus-cwm.htm | accessdate=2009-03-11}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>



== Focus ==
The {{convert|7000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} museum consists of five immersion exhibits that recreate aspects of Civil War medical issues: life in an army camp, evacuation of the wounded from the battlefront, a field dressing station, a field hospital and a military hospital ward. The exhibits incorporate surviving tools and equipment from the war, including the only known surviving Civil War surgeon’s tent, surgical kits, and items pertaining to veterinary medicine.<ref>{{cite news | author = | title =Museum of Civil War Medicine Examines How Medics Worked | publisher =Wheeling News-Register | date =September 10, 2007  | url =http://www.news-register.net/page/content.detail/id/52870.html?nav=608 | accessdate=2009-03-11}}</ref>

In 2006, the museum, in cooperation with the [[U.S. National Park Service]], began operating the Pry House Field Hospital Museum at the [[Antietam National Battlefield]].<ref>{{cite news | author =Karen Gardner | title =Pry House opens to public | publisher =Frederick News-Post | date =May 25, 2008 | url =http://www.fredericknewspost.com/sections/archives/display_detail.htm?StoryID=82874 | accessdate=2009-03-11}}</ref> The same year, the museum made its first foray into book publishing with the release of Robert G. Slawson’s ''Prologue to Change: African Americans in Medicine in the Civil War Era.''<ref>{{cite news | author =Nicholas C. Stern | title =Civil War author researches early African-American doctors | publisher =Frederick News-Post | date =February 1, 2009 | url =http://www.fredericknewspost.com/sections/archives/display_detail.htm?StoryID=92829 | accessdate=2009-03-11}}</ref> The museum is also the organizer for an annual national conference on Civil War-era medicine.<ref>{{cite news | author =Karen Gardner | title =Conference focuses on Civil War Medicine| publisher =Frederick News-Post | date =October 02, 2008| url =http://www.fredericknewspost.com/sections/archives/display_detail.htm?StoryID=88046 | accessdate=2009-03-11}}</ref>

